acket of carrot seeds, following him in every direction, sitting close to him at lunch, never leaving him alone.  The giggle and the wrinkled nose, pasted into ever scene, looped on repeat.  She found almost everything he said to be funny.{&1310}\par \tab Paul gathered a blanket around him and shuffled slowly into the kitchen.  The warmth of the stove woke what few parts of him were still asleep, and the the dream Paul had spent all morning on slowly began to rarrange itself back into place.{&1310}\par \tab“ATTENTION EVERYONE EVERYWHERE.  PLEASE GATHER.”{&1310}\par \tab The voice had come so loud, so unexpectadly, that it had bounced the bowl of pancake batter out of Paul’s hands - he now sat on the floor, coated in tan goop, as several car alarms yelled frantically in the distance.{&1310}\par \tab“EVERYONE.  THE RAPTURE IS NOW BEGINNING.  PLEASE GATHER.”{&1310}\par \tab Paul stood to see more clearly out the window - just a few miles away, what had to be an absolutely enormous man was sitting on top of a throne, which sat somewhere no further than three miles from Paul and Peter’s residence.  The man on the throne was dressed like some sort of king - he wore a long floral robe over what appeared to be armor, and a three-pronged crown on his head.  As he spoke he thumbed distractedly through a large pile of paperwork in his hands.{&1310}\par \tab Paul’s phone was ringing.  {&1310}\par \tab“Paul what the FUCK did you here that?!”{&1310}\par \tab“Yeah can you \i see \i0 it?!”{&1310}\par \tab“Yeah!  Christ he’s so loud - some guy was doing squats here, he litterally threw the weights through a mirror.”{&1310}\par \tab“Should we go?”{&1310}\par \tab“YOU SHOULD.”  The man on the throne anwered loudly, making an impatient beckoning motion in Paul’s general direction.{&1310}\par \tab“Ok just a second I’ll come pick you up;” Peter said, “Just let me grab my THIS WILL NOT TAKE LONG.  PLEASE STOP WHAT YOU ARE DOING you in a few!”{&1310}\par \tab Paul stood nervously on the front porch.  He paced a little bit and then stood still; leaned up against wooden banister above the garden his mother had paid a woman to plant last month.  The looming man was clearly visible in the distance, yet starring at him only seemed to make him appear less real.  Until the man moved, which was not terribly often, he looked like a giant statue, or an action figure held just so, that with one eye shut it looks large and distant.{&1310}\par \tab Peter pulled up still dripping from a shower.  If Paul had realized he was going to do that, he would have showered too - as it was, he was so preoccupied with the giant man that he had not even changed out of the clothes that were now tie-dyed brown with hardening pancake batter.{&1310}\par \tab“You smell like pancakes.” Peter remarked as he entered the car.  {&1310}\par \tab“I thought we were in a hurry.” {&1310}\par \tab Peter shrugged.  Outside helicoters speckled the sky, painting blips of shadow in the tangental morning light that was otherwise cloudless and clear.  {&1310}\par {&1310}\par {&1310}\par {&1310}\par {&1310}\par {&1310}\par {&1310}\par \f1 {&1310}\par }{&1310}
