ront porch.  He paced a little bit and then stood still; leaned up against wooden banister above the garden his mother had paid a woman to plant last month.  The looming man was clearly visible in the distance, yet starring at him only seemed to make him appear less real.  Until the man moved, which was not terribly often, he looked like a giant statue, or an action figure held just so, that with one eye shut it looks large and distant.{&1310}\par \tab Peter pulled up still dripping from a shower.  If Paul had realized he was going to do that, he would have showered too - as it was, he was so preoccupied with the giant man that he had not even changed out of the clothes that were now tie-dyed brown with hardening pancake batter.{&1310}\par \tab“You smell like pancakes.” Peter remarked as he entered the car.  {&1310}\par \tab“I thought we were in a hurry.” {&1310}\par \tab Peter shrugged.  The block was empty except for the two boys, and it appears as though they were now some of the last few people still dragging their feet.{&1310}\par \tab“SARAH.  I CAN SEE YOU UNDER YOUR BED.  DO NOT BE FRIGHTENED, WE CANNOT BEGIN UNTIL EVERYONE IS HERE.  PAUL AND PETER - OH, YOU’RE ON YOUR WAY.”{&1310}\par \tab“We're not late, are we?”{&1310}\par \tab“Looks like a little.”{&1310}\par \tab Peter nodded solemnly at the bizzare, traffic-less oneway they drove down.{&1310}\par \tab“So how did it go yesterday?  You never told me.”{&1310}\par \tab“You want to talk about this now?”{&1310}\par \tab“I'm just curious.”  Peter had turned the music off from the moment he left the gym.  Nothing sounded quite right this morning.{&1310}\par \tab“It was just me and her, and a bunch of homeschooled kids.”{&1310}\par \tab“What?”{&1310}\par \tab“We were the only ones from our school.”{&1310}\par \tab“So, you were the only one she invited?”{&1310}\par \tab“Or the only one that showed up.  What does that mean?”{&1310}\par \tab“I don’t know, did she talk to you?”{&1310}\par \tab“About as much as everyone else - there was this one kid - wouldn’t fucking leave me alone.  Every time Rebekkah came over he was talking at me so she just walked around us.”{&1310}\par \tab“Ah,” Peter sighed sympathetically.  “So, what’d you end up doing?”{&1310}\par \tab“I planted the fucking seeds and then I left.”{&1310}\par \tab“Did you say goodbye or like, ‘thanks for inviting me’, or . . .”{&1310}\par \tab“No.”  Paul slid down in the passanger seat.  “I just left.”{&1310}\par \tab“Dude she wouldn’t have invited you if she didn’t want you there.  She came up to YOU, remember.  I get that that kid was bothering you, but you can’t be all bitter because of that.”{&1310}\par \tab“You weren’t there.”  Paul curled into the fabric seat, away from Peter, his eyes fixed out the window.  Helicopters blew across the sky in tiny blips, followed by monsterous shadows that raced across the pavement in the tangental morning light. {&1310}\par \tab About a mile from the base of the throne, the streets became to congested with empty cars; some were parked neatly against the curb, while others were parked perpandicular to the street.{&1310}\par \tab“Guess we’re walking from here,” Peter lamented, as he pulled the car up on to a decorative median.{&1310}\par \tab“What the hell! Why are you parking in the flowers?”{&1310}\par \tab Peter looked at Paul blankly.  “Everyone is just - everyone’s parking like this.”{&1310}\par \tab“You could have just \i stopped\i0 .  Christ dude.”{&1310}\par \tab“KAREN, TURN LEFT, YOU WILL GET HERE FASTER.  YES, THERE’S NO TRAFFIC ON DOWNING RIGHT NOW . . . IT DOESN’T MATTER IF ITS A ONEWAY, YOU’RE THE ONLY PERSON STILL DRIVING.”{&1310}\par \tab“So do you think you’re going to see her again?” Peter negotiated his footing over the top of a motorcycle that had been parked in the middle of the sidewalk, that was now blocked in by a minivan and a Ford Taurus.  {&1310}\par \tab“Who, Rebekkah?  I guess next year.”{&1310}\par \tab“Isn't there going to be, like, more gardening over the summer?  Watering and all that?”{&1310}\par \tab“She didn’t say anything about it.  She would have told me about it if she wanted me there.”{&1310}\par \tab“She might’ve if you hadn’t just walked out.”{&1310}\par \tab“Can we not talk about this anymore?”  The sound of people was growing louder, the cars were packed like Tetris against eachother.  The base of the throne and the man on top were so close now that looking up at him hurt your neck.  It was almost night in his shadow, where Paul and Peter pushed their way through a row of shrubbery lining the mall.{&1310}\par \tab {&1310}\par {&1310}\par {&1310}\par \f1 {&1310}\par }{&1310}
