acket of carrot seeds, following him in every direction, sitting close to him at lunch, never leaving him alone.  The giggle and the wrinkled nose, pasted into ever scene, looped on repeat.  She found almost everything he said to be funny.{&1310}\par \tab Paul gathered a blanket around him and shuffled slowly into the kitchen.  The warmth of the stove woke what few parts of him were still asleep, and the the dream Paul had spent all morning on slowly began to rarrange itself back into place.{&1310}\par \tab“ATTENTION EVERYONE EVERYWHERE.  PLEASE GATHER.”{&1310}\par \tab The voice had come so loud, so unexpectadly, that it had bounced the bowl of pancake batter out of Paul’s hands - he now sat on the floor, coated in tan goop, as several car alarms yelled frantically in the distance.{&1310}\par \tab“EVERYONE.  THE RAPTURE IS NOW BEGINNING.  PLEASE GATHER.”{&1310}\par \tab Paul stood to see more clearly out the window - just a few miles away, what had to be an absolutely enormous man was sitting on top of a throne, which sat somewhere no further than three miles from Paul and Peter’s residence.  The man on the throne was dressed like some sort of king - he wore a long floral robe over what appeared to be armor, and a three-pronged crown on his head.  As he spoke he thumbed distractedly through a large pile of paperwork in his hands.{&1310}\par \tab Paul’s phone was ringing.  {&1310}\par \tab“Paul what the FUCK did you here that?!”{&1310}\par \tab“Yeah can you \i see \i0 it?!”{&1310}\par \tab“Yeah!  Christ he’s so loud - some guy was doing squats here, he litterally threw the weights through a mirror.”{&1310}\par \tab“Should we go?”{&1310}\par \tab“YOU SHOULD.”  The man on the throne anwered loudly, making an impatient beckoning motion in Paul’s general direction.{&1310}\par \tab“Ok just a second I’ll come pick you up;” Peter said, “Just let me grab my THIS WILL NOT TAKE LONG.  PLEASE STOP WHAT YOU ARE DOING you in a few!”{&1310}\par \tab Paul waited nervously on the front porch.  He paced a little bit and then stood still; leaned up against wooden banister above the garden his mother had paid a woman to plant last month.  The looming man was clearly visible in the distance, yet starring at him only seemed to make him appear less real.  Until the man moved, which was not terribly often, he looked like a giant statue, or an action figure held just so, that with one eye shut it looks large and distant.{&1310}\par \tab Peter pulled up still dripping from a shower.  If Paul had realized he was going to do that, he would have showered too - as it was, he was so preoccupied with the giant man that he had not even changed out of the clothes that were now tie-dyed brown with hardening pancake batter.{&1310}\par \tab“You smell like pancakes.” Peter remarked as he entered the car.  {&1310}\par \tab“I thought we were in a hurry.” {&1310}\par \tab Peter shrugged.  The block was empty except for the two boys, and it appears as though they were now some of the last few people still dragging their feet.{&1310}\par \tab“SARAH.  I CAN SEE YOU UNDER YOUR BED.  DO NOT BE FRIGHTENED, WE CANNOT BEGIN UNTIL EVERYONE IS HERE.  PAUL AND PETER - OH, YOU’RE ON YOUR WAY.”{&1310}\par \tab“We're not late, are we?”{&1310}\par \tab“Looks like a little.”{&1310}\par \tab Peter nodded solemnly at the bizzare, traffic-less street they drove down.{&1310}\par \tab“So how did it go yesterday?  You never told me.”{&1310}\par \tab“You want to talk about this now?”{&1310}\par \tab“I'm just curious.”  Peter had turned the music off from the moment he left the gym.  Nothing sounded quite right this morning.{&1310}\par \tab“It was just me and her, and a bunch of homeschooled kids.”{&1310}\par \tab“What?”{&1310}\par \tab“We were the only ones from our school.”{&1310}\par \tab“So, you were the only one she invited?”{&1310}\par \tab“Or the only one that showed up.  What does that mean?”{&1310}\par \tab“I don’t know, did she talk to you?”{&1310}\par \tab“About as much as everyone else - there was this one kid - wouldn’t fucking leave me alone.  Every time Rebekkah came over he was talking at me so she just walked around us.”{&1310}\par \tab“Ah,” Peter sighed sympathetically.  “So, what’d you end up doing?”{&1310}\par \tab“I planted the fucking seeds and then I left.”{&1310}\par \tab“Did you say goodbye or like, ‘thanks for inviting me’, or . . .”{&1310}\par \tab“No.”  Paul slid down in the passanger seat.  “I just left.”{&1310}\par \tab“Dude she wouldn’t have invited you if she didn’t want you there.  She came up to YOU, remember.  I get that that kid was bothering you, but you can’t be all bitter because of that.”{&1310}\par \tab“You weren’t there.”  Paul curled into the fabric seat, away from Peter, his eyes fixed out the window.  Helicopters blew across the sky in tiny blips, followed by monsterous shadows that raced across the pavement in the tangental morning light. {&1310}\par \tab About a mile from the base of the throne, the streets became congested with empty cars; some were parked neatly against the curb, while others were parked perpandicular to the street.{&1310}\par \tab“Guess we’re walking from here,” Peter groaned, as he pulled the car up on to a decorative median.{&1310}\par \tab“What the hell! Why are you parking in the flowers?”{&1310}\par \tab Peter looked at Paul blankly.  “Everyone is just - everyone’s parking like this.”{&1310}\par \tab“You could have just \i stopped\i0 .  Christ dude.”{&1310}\par \tab“KAREN, TURN LEFT, YOU WILL GET HERE FASTER.  YES, THERE’S NO TRAFFIC ON DOWNING RIGHT NOW . . . IT DOESN’T MATTER IF ITS A ONEWAY, YOU’RE THE ONLY PERSON STILL DRIVING.”{&1310}\par \tab“So do you think you’re going to see her again?”{&1310}\par \tab“Who, Rebekkah?  I guess next year.”{&1310}\par \tab“Isn't there going to be, like, more gardening over the summer?  Watering and all that?”{&1310}\par \tab“She didn’t say anything about it.  She would have told me about it if she wanted me there.”{&1310}\par \tab“She might’ve if you hadn’t just walked out.”{&1310}\par \tab“Can we not talk about this anymore?”  The sound of people was growing louder, the cars packed like Tetris against eachother.  The base of the throne and the man on top were so close now that looking up at him hurt your neck.  It was almost night in his shadow, where Paul and Peter pushed their way through a row of shrubbery lining the mall. - into the mall parking lot where the entire town stood waiting.{&1310}\par \tab Robert had landed directly on top of the north side of the mall, crushing it completely into the ground.  {&1310}\par \tab“Ahh, that was the \i good\i0  side of the mall.” Peter lamented.  “RIght on top of the Orange Julius.”{&1310}\par \tab The crowd was handling the situation in different ways; however, all of the ways could be grouped into three main categories - fear, panic, and suspense.  A large group stood huddled in a circle, arms over shoulders.  A man darted out of the doors of a neigboring best buy with a laptop clutched to his chest.{&1310}\par \tab“MICHAEL, PUT THAT BACK!  I SWEAR.  WE CAN’T GET ANYTHING DONE IF YOU DON’T - PUT IT . . . THANK YOU.”{&1310}\par \tab The most popular activity, by far, was from the third category.  People stood, sat, and leaned nervously on all available architecture, eyes transfixed on the solemn face of the giant in front of them.{&1310}\par \tab The scene reminded Peter of a tailgate party - one that no one seemed to be particuarl enjoying.  A tailgate party for a losing home team, mixed with the line of a DMV.  Peter, for one, was mildly excited.  This was, hands down, the most fascinating thing to have happened to him in a very long time.{&1310}\par \tab“Do you want to go closer?”{&1310}\par \tab“No, I’m fine.”  Paul would have been fine watching from home.  The man on the throne continued to call out instrustions to individuals while absently sorting through his stack of department-store sized papers, the rustling of which created winds that blew dust around the lot and shook the branches of trees.  One piece slipped from the stack, creating a giant shadow over the crowd.  The people below shrieked in horror as the sheet of looseleaf floated lazily towards them.  The man attempted to catch it, the paper bouncing off his finger tips and out of grasp a few times before he finally snatched it about thirty feet from the ground.{&1310}\par \tab Paul would have been fine listening from his bed, beneath the covers.  He scanned the crowd nervously, flinching away from the endless ribbon of faces.  And then there was one he recognized.  Rebekkah floated listlessy through the crowd, and then, like at school, eye contact, and here she came again.{&1310}\par \tab To say that this is exactly what Paul had feared would be partially true.  The feeling contradicted in his mind but what he felt was fear.  {&1310}\par \tab {&1310}\par {&1310}\par {&1310}\par \f1 {&1310}\par }{&1310}
